    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" subtype="primary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#JP" source="#autopsy">
                    <ab>
                         <lb n="1"/><w>χρη<supplied reason="lost">στ</supplied><gap reason="lost" unit="character" atLeast="1" atMost="2"/></w> <supplied reason="lost"><w>καὶ</w></supplied>
                        <lb n="2"/>ἄ<hi rend="ligature">με</hi><unclear>μ</unclear><supplied reason="lost">πτ</supplied><gap reason="lost" unit="character" atLeast="1" atMost="2"/>
                        <lb n="3"/>ἐβίω<supplied reason="lost">σε</supplied> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                        <lb n="4"/><g ref="#interpunct">·</g><orig><unclear>Μ</unclear></orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                    </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus" resp="#JP">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text based on autopsy</note></app>
                    <app loc="1"><note>The ending of χρηστὸς is uncertain</note></app>
                    <app loc="2"><note>The ending of ἄμεμπτος is uncertain (and the alternative spelling ἄμενπτος also possible)</note></app>
                    <app loc="4"><note>N is just possible, but there is no trace of the vertical to the right.</note></app>
                    </listApp> 
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>[----] worthy and blameless, lived [---]</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#JP">
                <p>The name of the deceased is missing from above line 1. The formula χρηστὸς καὶ αμ̓́εμπτος is distinctive to the Syracusan region. The verb ἐβίωσε(ν) instead of ἔζησε(ν) is relatively rare, although attested in use in Sicily. The Μ preceded by an interpunct in the final line is likely to be a numeral from the age of the deceased, with ἔτη to be restored at the end of line 3.</p>
            </div>
